’Щ@09dfc781a356063cde23afdba142168c9d3954ec44f3f2b4b7891da86999a308Ъ.Title: title: Top 5 Nushell Hacks
Path: 1. ends-with / starts-with operators
Content:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
вқҜ ls | where name ends-with .toml or name starts-with Car
в•ӯв”Җ#в”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җnameв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җtypeв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җsizeв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җmodifiedв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ Cargo.lock          в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ 165.4 KB в”Ӯ 22 minutes ago в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ Cargo.toml          в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ   6.4 KB в”Ӯ an hour ago    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ Cross.toml          в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ    666 B в”Ӯ an hour ago    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ rust-toolchain.toml в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ   1.1 KB в”Ӯ an hour ago    в”Ӯ
в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ

```
’Щ@265f5bf3a234447a43a1e784d2f5f2ae5327308f5b79ba64e73af00fcc100e4aЪTitle: title: Top 5 Nushell Hacks
Path: 2. easter egg
Content:
Did you know that when you start nushell, the 
``$env.CMD_DURATION_MS``
 value of 0823 is an easter egg? 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/releases/tag/0.2.0] It's nushell's first public release date month day
.
’Щ@a77530dd9eb75671c58793b09756c5c2da32094e02754b52a777c524428530ddЪTitle: title: Top 5 Nushell Hacks
Path: 3. abbr
Content:
With this menu and keybinding configured appropriately in your config.nu file, you can hit 
``ctrl+space``
 and your alias abbreviation will expand to it's non-abbreviated form.
For instance, if you have this alias
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
alias gwch = git whatchanged -p --abbrev-commit --pretty=medium

```
and then you type 
``gwch<ctrl+space>``
 it will expand on the prompt line to 
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
git whatchanged -p --abbrev-commit --pretty=medium

```
’Щ@aa8878ad9ef3626af3b1529f94019f82b7af6e47b68ec4ecf183718e3d4eb017ЪTitle: title: Top 5 Nushell Hacks
Path: keybinding
Content:
```Fenced(Borrowed("js"))
  {
    name: abbr
    modifier: control
    keycode: space
    mode: [emacs, vi_normal, vi_insert]
    event: [
    { send: menu name: abbr_menu }
    { edit: insertchar, value: ' '}
    ]
  }

```
’Щ@6fb53809cfe5adb6d00961fdc9d165c30b64b221f46710636e802cccdea3df37Ъ#Title: title: Top 5 Nushell Hacks
Path: menu
Content:
```Fenced(Borrowed("js"))
    {
      name: abbr_menu
      only_buffer_difference: false
      marker: "рҹ‘Җ "
      type: {
        layout: columnar
        columns: 1
        col_width: 20
        col_padding: 2
      }
      style: {
        text: green
        selected_text: green_reverse
        description_text: yellow
      }
      source: { |buffer, position|
        scope aliases
        | where name == $buffer
        | each { |elt| {value: $elt.expansion }}
      }
    }

```
’Щ@7a6483e805cc2342e8d6e6a7e4ac5475e5ec7f8e9c738061ea639bc5693e9970ЪыTitle: title: Top 5 Nushell Hacks
Path:  with 
Content:
``where``
``ls``
People often forget that the 
``=~``
 and 
``!~``
 are regular expression operators, which means you can do a case-insensitive search like this.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
вқҜ ls | where name =~ '(?i)car'
в•ӯв”Җ#в”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җnameв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җtypeв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җsizeв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җmodifiedв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ Cargo.lock в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ 160.6 KB в”Ӯ 8 hours ago    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ Cargo.toml в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ   6.4 KB в”Ӯ 8 hours ago    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ car.txt    в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ      0 B в”Ӯ 11 seconds ago в”Ӯ
в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ

```
’Щ@cf1dc7305cf8b1cd7d1595c7b364ce7d55a81dc1b0e1aa3b76694fa019acd6f4ЪёTitle: title: Top 5 Nushell Hacks
Path: 5. the magic of nushell datatype closures
Content:
In your config.nu file you can have themes that color nushell datatypes a particular color. One thing that is sometimes overlooked is that these colors can also be closures, like the one below for 
``string``
.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
string: {|| if $in =~ '^#[a-fA-F\d]+' { $in } else { 'default' } }

```
This allows nushell to detect anything that looks like a hex color and display that color in nushell.
This allows you to take a file like the x11 rgb.txt file and parse it into colors.
rgb.txt
```Fenced(Borrowed("nushell"))
вқҜ open ~/Downloads/rgb.txt | lines | last 10
в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ 139   0   0        DarkRed        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ 144 238 144        light green    в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ 144 238 144        LightGreen     в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ 220  20  60        crimson        в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 4 в”Ӯ  75   0 130        indigo         в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 5 в”Ӯ 128 128   0        olive          в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 6 в”Ӯ 102  51 153        rebecca purple в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 7 в”Ӯ 102  51 153        RebeccaPurple  в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 8 в”Ӯ 192 192 192        silver         в”Ӯ
в”Ӯ 9 в”Ӯ   0 128 128        teal           в”Ӯ
в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ

```
And after parsing the file looks similar to this.

rgb
